This the accuser does not deny, but he finds fault with it, so that, in the case cf Cornelius, his pleas meet with approval, yet punishment is demanded3 in the case of Pompeius, his pleas are slighted‚ but there is no penalty except that his reputation may suffer. Thus they wish the fortunes of a man entirely innocent, and the act of a general of the highest distinction, to be condemned together. Therefore the civil rights of Cornelius, the act of Pompey, are now challenged in the eom-ts. You admit that this man was born in a most honourable position in his native state, and that from his earliest years, leaving all his own affairs, he was engaged in our wars under our generals, and that there is no toil, no siege, no battle, in which he has not taken a part. All this is not only most meritorious‚ but belongs peculiarly to Cornelius, and in this exists no ground of accusation. 7. Of what, then, is he accused'?
